# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: areca-nut
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] The **16th century** begins with the Julian year 1501 (MDI) and ends with either the Julian or the Gregorian year 1600 (MDC) (depending on the reckoning used; the Gregorian calendar introduced a lapse of 10 days in October 1582).
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] The Habsburg Spanish Empire, Portuguese Empire, Ottoman Empire, Safavid Persia, Mughal India and Ming China were the most powerful and hegemonic states.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] The Renaissance in Italy and Europe saw the emergence of important artists, authors and scientists, and led to the foundation of important subjects which include accounting and political science.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] Copernicus proposed the heliocentric universe, which was met with strong resistance, and Tycho Brahe refuted the theory of celestial spheres through observational measurement of the 1572 appearance of a Milky Way supernova.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] These events directly challenged the long-held notion of an immutable universe supported by Ptolemy and Aristotle, and led to major revolutions in astronomy and science.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] Galileo Galilei became a champion of the new sciences, invented the first thermometer and made substantial contributions in the fields of physics and astronomy, becoming a major figure in the Scientific Revolution in Europe.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] Spain and Portugal colonized large parts of Central and South America, followed by France and England in Northern America and the Lesser Antilles.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] The Portuguese became the masters of trade between Brazil, the coasts of Africa, and their possessions in the Indies, whereas the Spanish came to dominate the Greater Antilles, Mexico, Peru, and opened trade across the Pacific Ocean, linking the Americas with the Indies.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] English and French privateers began to practice persistent theft of Spanish and Portuguese treasures.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] This era of colonialism established mercantilism as the leading school of economic thought, where the economic system was viewed as a zero-sum game in which any gain by one party required a loss by another.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] The mercantilist doctrine encouraged the many intra-European wars of the period and arguably fueled European expansion and imperialism throughout the world until the 19th century or early 20th century.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] The Reformation in central and northern Europe gave a major blow to the authority of the papacy and the Catholic Church.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] In England, the British-Italian Alberico Gentili wrote the first book on public international law and divided secularism from canon law and Catholic theology.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] European politics became dominated by religious conflicts, with the groundwork for the epochal Thirty Years' War being laid towards the end of the century.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] In the Middle East, the Ottoman Empire continued to expand, with the sultan taking the title of caliph, while dealing with a resurgent Persia.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] Iran and Iraq were caught by a major popularity of the Shia sect of Islam under the rule of the Safavid dynasty of warrior-mystics, providing grounds for a Persia independent of the majority-Sunni Muslim world.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] In the Indian subcontinent, following the defeat of the Delhi Sultanate and Vijayanagara Empire, new powers emerged, the Sur Empire founded by Sher Shah Suri, Deccan sultanates, Rajput states, and the Mughal Empire by Emperor Babur, a direct descendant of Timur and Genghis Khan.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] His successors Humayun and Akbar, enlarged the empire to include most of South Asia.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] Japan suffered a severe civil war at this time, known as the Sengoku period, and emerged from it as a unified nation under Toyotomi Hideyoshi.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] China was ruled by the Ming dynasty, which was becoming increasingly isolationist, coming into conflict with Japan over the control of Korea as well as Japanese pirates.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] In Africa, Christianity had begun to spread in Central Africa and Southern Africa.
[src:areca-nut/16th-century] Until the Scramble for Africa in the late 19th century, most of Africa was left uncolonized.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:areca-nut/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:areca-nut/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:areca-nut/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] It is popular throughout West Africa, and goes by many names including **apio**, **ogoglo**, **ogogoro** (**Ogog'**), **VC10,** **Kill Me Quick**, **Efie Nipa, Kele, Kumepreko, Anferewoase, Apiatiti, Home Boy, Nana Drobo, One Touch** among others.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] It is also known as sapele water, kparaga, kai-kai, Sun gbalaja, egun inu igo meaning *The Masquerade in the Bottle*, push-me-push-you, and/or crim-kena, sonsé ("do you do it?" in Yoruba language).
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] In the Igbo language it is known as *Akpuru achia*.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Other Nigerian epithets include: *Udi Ogagan*, *Agbagba* Urhobo, as well *OHMS* (Our Home Made Stuff), *Iced Water*, *Push Me, I Push You* and *Craze man in the bottle*.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Ghanaian moonshine is referred to as akpeteshie.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] With British colonization of what became known as the Gold Coast, such local brewing was outlawed in the early 1930s.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Dotse about his life under British colonial rule: "Our contention was that the drink the white man brought is the same as ours.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The white men's contention was that ours was too strong...Before the white men came we were using akpeteshie.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] But when they came they banned it, probably because they wanted to make sales on their own liquor.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] When you had a visitor whom you knew very well, then you ordered that kpótomenui be brought.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The name "akpeteshie" was given to the drink with its prohibition: the word comes from the Ga language (*ape te shie*, the act of hiding) spoken in greater Accra and means *they are hiding*, referring to the secretive way in which non-European inhabitants were forced to consume the beverage.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Despite being outlawed, illicit spirits remained commonplace, with reports that even schoolboys were able to easily obtain akpeteshie through the 1930s.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Demand for akpeteshie and the profits to be made from its sale was enough to encourage the spread of sugar cane cultivation in the Anlo region of Ghana.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Distillation was legalized with decolonization and Ghanaian independence.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The first factory was established in the Volta Region, taking advantage of the area's supply of sugar cane plantations.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Ogogoro is distilled from the juice of Raffia palm trees.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] An incision is made in the trunk and a gourd placed outside it for collection, which is collected a day or two later.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] After extraction, the sap is boiled to form steam, which subsequently condenses and is collected for consumption.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is distilled from palm wine or sugarcane juice.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] This sweetened liquid or wine is first fermented in a large barrels, sometimes with the help of yeast.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] After this first stage of fermentation, fires are built under the barrels in order to bring the liquid to a boil and pass the resulting vapor through a copper pipe within cooling barrels, where it condenses and drips into sieved jars.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The boiled juice then undergoes a distillation.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The resulting spirit is between 40 and 50% alcohol by volume.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is not professionally bottled or sealed, but instead poured into unlabeled used bottles.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The spirit can be bought wholesale from a brewer or by the glass at boutiques and bars.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Although not professionally advertised, the drink is very popular.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] This is partially due to its price, which is lower than that of other professionally bottled or imported drinks.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Its relative cheapness makes it a drink associated more with the poor, but even those who can afford better quality are said to consume the spirit in secret.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The potency of the liquor heavily affects the bodily senses, providing a feeling likened to that of a knockout punch.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Practiced drinkers can be seen acknowledging receipt by blowing out air or pounding their chest.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] As drink and commodity, respectively, ogogoro carries substantial cultural and economic significance within Nigeria.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] It is an essential part of numerous religious and social ceremonies; Burutu (Ijaw) priests pour it onto the ground as offerings to contact their gods, while fathers of Nigerian brides use it as a libation by which they provide their official blessing to a wedding.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] The economic facets of ogogoro have been equally salient throughout recent Nigerian history.
[src:areca-nut/akpeteshie] Many poor Nigerian families homebrew the drink as a means of economic subsistence, many of whom sell shots of it on city street corners.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In organic chemistry, an **aldehyde** (/ˈældɪhaɪd/) (lat.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] *al*cohol *dehyd*rogenatum, dehydrogenated alcohol) is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure R−CH=O.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The functional group itself (without the "R" side chain) can be referred to as an **aldehyde** but can also be classified as a **formyl group**.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehydes are a common motif in many chemicals important in technology and biology.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehyde molecules have a central carbon atom that is connected by a double bond to oxygen, a single bond to hydrogen and another single bond to a third substituent, which is carbon or, in the case of formaldehyde, hydrogen.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The central carbon is often described as being sp2-hybridized.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The C=O bond length is about 120–122 picometers.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehydes have properties that are diverse and that depend on the remainder of the molecule.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Smaller aldehydes such as formaldehyde and acetaldehyde are soluble in water, and the volatile aldehydes have pungent odors.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehydes can be identified by spectroscopic methods.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Using IR spectroscopy, they display a strong *ν*CO band near 1700 cm−1.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In their 1H NMR spectra, the formyl hydrogen center absorbs near *δ*H 9.5 to 10, which is a distinctive part of the spectrum.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This signal shows the characteristic coupling to any protons on the α carbon with a small coupling constant typically less than 3.0 Hz.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The 13C NMR spectra of aldehydes and ketones gives a suppressed (weak) but distinctive signal at *δ*C 190 to 205.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Important aldehydes and related compounds.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Traces of many aldehydes are found in essential oils and often contribute to their pleasant odours, including cinnamaldehyde, cilantro, and vanillin.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Possibly due to the high reactivity of the formyl group, aldehydes are not commonly found in organic "building block" molecules, such as amino acids, nucleic acids, and lipids.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] However, most sugars are derivatives of aldehydes.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] These aldoses exist as hemiacetals, a sort of masked form of the parent aldehyde.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] For example, in aqueous solution only a tiny fraction of glucose exists as the aldehyde.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Of the several methods for preparing aldehydes, one dominant technology is hydroformylation.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Hydroformylation is conducted on a very large scale for diverse aldehydes.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] It involves treatment of the alkene with a mixture of hydrogen gas and carbon monoxide in the presence of a metal catalyst.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The largest operations involve methanol and ethanol respectively to formaldehyde and acetaldehyde, which are produced on multimillion ton scale annually.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Other large scale aldehydes are produced by autoxidation of hydrocarbons: benzaldehyde from toluene, acrolein from propylene, and methacrolein from isobutene.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In the Wacker process, oxidation of ethylene to acetaldehyde in the presence of copper and palladium catalysts, is also used.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] "Green" and cheap oxygen (or air) is the oxidant of choice.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Laboratories may instead apply a wide variety of specialized oxidizing agents, which are often consumed stoichiometrically.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Oxidation can be achieved by heating the alcohol with an acidified solution of potassium dichromate.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In this case, excess dichromate will further oxidize the aldehyde to a carboxylic acid, so either the aldehyde is distilled out as it forms (if volatile) or milder reagents such as PCC are used.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] A variety of reagent systems achieve aldehydes under chromium-free conditions.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] One such are the hypervalent organoiodine compounds (i.e., IBX acid, Dess–Martin periodinane), although these often also oxidize the α position.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] A Lux-Flood acid will activate various sulfoxides (e.g. the Swern oxidation), and amine oxides convert alkyl halides to aldehydes (e.g., the Ganem oxidation).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Sterically-hindered nitroxyls (i.e., TEMPO) can catalyze aldehyde formation with a cheaper oxidant.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Alternatively, vicinal diols or their oxidized sequelae (acyloins or α-hydroxy acids) can be oxidized with cleavage to two aldehydes or an aldehyde and carbon dioxide.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehydes participate in many reactions.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] From the biological perspective, the key reactions involve addition of nucleophiles to the formyl carbon in the formation of imines (oxidative deamination) and hemiacetals (structures of aldose sugars).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Because of resonance stabilization of the conjugate base, an α-hydrogen in an aldehyde is weakly acidic with a p*K*a near 17.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The formyl proton itself does not readily undergo deprotonation.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehydes (except those without an alpha carbon, or without protons on the alpha carbon, such as formaldehyde and benzaldehyde) can exist in either the keto or the enol tautomer.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Keto–enol tautomerism is catalyzed by either acid or base.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In neutral solution, the enol is the minority tautomer, reversing several times per second.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] But it becomes the dominant tautomer in strong acid or base solutions, and enolized aldehydes undergo nucleophilic attack at the α position.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The formyl group can be readily reduced to a primary alcohol (−CH2OH).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Typically this conversion is accomplished by catalytic hydrogenation either directly or by transfer hydrogenation.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Stoichiometric reductions are also popular, as can be effected with sodium borohydride.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The formyl group readily oxidizes to the corresponding carboxyl group (−COOH).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The preferred oxidant in industry is oxygen or air.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In the laboratory, popular oxidizing agents include potassium permanganate, nitric acid, chromium(VI) oxide, and chromic acid.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The combination of manganese dioxide, cyanide, acetic acid and methanol will convert the aldehyde to a methyl ester.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Another oxidation reaction is the basis of the *silver-mirror test*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This reagent converts aldehydes to carboxylic acids without attacking carbon–carbon double bonds.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The name *silver-mirror test* arises because this reaction produces a precipitate of silver, whose presence can be used to test for the presence of an aldehyde.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] A further oxidation reaction involves Fehling's reagent as a test.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The Cu2+ complex ions are reduced to a red-brick-coloured Cu2O precipitate.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aromatic aldehydes, such as benzaldehyde, do not give a positive Fehling's test, because they are not easily oxidized by mild oxidizing agents like Fehling's reagent.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The benzene ring provides stability, while steric hindrance prevents the formation of the required hydrated anion intermediate.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] If the aldehyde cannot form an enolate (e.g., benzaldehyde), addition of strong base induces the Cannizzaro reaction.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This reaction results in disproportionation, producing a mixture of alcohol and carboxylic acid.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Nucleophiles add readily to the carbonyl group.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In many cases, a water molecule is removed after the addition takes place; in this case, the reaction is classed as an addition–elimination or addition–condensation reaction.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] There are many variations of nucleophilic addition reactions.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In the acetalisation reaction, under acidic or basic conditions, an alcohol adds to the carbonyl group and a proton is transferred to form a hemiacetal.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Under acidic conditions, the hemiacetal and the alcohol can further react to form an acetal and water.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Simple hemiacetals are usually unstable, although cyclic ones such as glucose can be stable.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Acetals are stable, but revert to the aldehyde in the presence of acid.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Aldehydes can react with water to form hydrates, R−CH(OH)2.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] These diols are stable when strong electron withdrawing groups are present, as in chloral hydrate.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The mechanism of formation is identical to hemiacetal formation.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Another aldehyde molecule can also act as the nucleophile to give polymeric or oligomeric acetals called paraldehydes.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In alkylimino-de-oxo-bisubstitution, a primary or secondary amine adds to the carbonyl group and a proton is transferred from the nitrogen to the oxygen atom to create a carbinolamine.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In the case of a primary amine, a water molecule can be eliminated from the carbinolamine intermediate to yield an imine or its trimer, a hexahydrotriazine This reaction is catalyzed by acid.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Hydroxylamine (NH2OH) can also add to the carbonyl group.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] After the elimination of water, this results in an oxime.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] An ammonia derivative of the form H2NNR2 such as hydrazine (H2NNH2) or 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine can also be the nucleophile and after the elimination of water, resulting in the formation of a hydrazone, which are usually orange crystalline solids.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This reaction forms the basis of a test for aldehydes and ketones.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The cyano group in HCN can add to the carbonyl group to form cyanohydrins, R−CH(OH)CN.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In this reaction the CN− ion is the nucleophile that attacks the partially positive carbon atom of the carbonyl group.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The mechanism involves a pair of electrons from the carbonyl-group double bond transferring to the oxygen atom, leaving it single-bonded to carbon and giving the oxygen atom a negative charge.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This intermediate ion rapidly reacts with H+, such as from the HCN molecule, to form the alcohol group of the cyanohydrin.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Organometallic compounds, such as organolithium reagents, Grignard reagents, or acetylides, undergo nucleophilic addition reactions, yielding a substituted alcohol group.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Related reactions include organostannane additions, Barbier reactions, and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In the aldol reaction, the metal enolates of ketones, esters, amides, and carboxylic acids add to aldehydes to form β-hydroxycarbonyl compounds (aldols).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Acid or base-catalyzed dehydration then leads to α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The combination of these two steps is known as the aldol condensation.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The Prins reaction occurs when a nucleophilic alkene or alkyne reacts with an aldehyde as electrophile.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The product of the Prins reaction varies with reaction conditions and substrates employed.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This reaction is used as a test for aldehydes and is useful for separation or purification of aldehydes.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] A **dialdehyde** is an organic chemical compound with two aldehyde groups.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The nomenclature of dialdehydes have the ending *-dial* or sometimes *-dialdehyde*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Short aliphatic dialdehydes are sometimes named after the diacid from which they can be derived.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] An example is butanedial, which is also called succinaldehyde (from succinic acid).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Some aldehydes are substrates for aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes which metabolize aldehydes in the body.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] There are toxicities associated with some aldehydes that are related to neurodegenerative disease, heart disease, and some types of cancer.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Of all aldehydes, formaldehyde is produced on the largest scale, about 6000000 tons per year.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] It is mainly used in the production of resins when combined with urea, melamine, and phenol (e.g., Bakelite).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] It is a precursor to methylene diphenyl diisocyanate ("MDI"), a precursor to polyurethanes.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The second main aldehyde is butyraldehyde, of which about 2500000 tons per year are prepared by hydroformylation.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] It is the principal precursor to 2-ethylhexanol, which is used as a plasticizer.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Acetaldehyde once was a dominating product, but production levels have declined to less than 1000000 tons per year because it mainly served as a precursor to acetic acid, which is now prepared by carbonylation of methanol.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Many other aldehydes find commercial applications, often as precursors to alcohols, the so-called oxo alcohols, which are used in detergents.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Some aldehydes are produced only on a small scale (less than 1000 tons per year) and are used as ingredients in flavours and perfumes such as Chanel No.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Fresh, green, citrusy and nutty notes in perfumes are often due to aldehydes.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] These include cinnamaldehyde and its derivatives, citral, and lilial.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The common names for aldehydes do not strictly follow official guidelines, such as those recommended by IUPAC, but these rules are useful.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In other cases, such as when a −CHO group is attached to a ring, the suffix *-carbaldehyde* may be used.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] Thus, C6H11CHO is known as *cyclohexanecarbaldehyde*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] If the presence of another functional group demands the use of a suffix, the aldehyde group is named with the prefix *formyl-*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This prefix is preferred to *methanoyl-*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] If the compound is a natural product or a carboxylic acid, the prefix *oxo-* may be used to indicate which carbon atom is part of the aldehyde group; for example, CHOCH2COOH is named *2-oxoethanoic acid*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] If replacing the aldehyde group with a carboxyl group (−COOH) would yield a carboxylic acid with a trivial name, the aldehyde may be named by replacing the suffix *-ic acid* or *-oic acid* in this trivial name by *-aldehyde*.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The word *aldehyde* was coined by Justus von Liebig as a contraction of the Latin ***al**cohol **dehyd**rogenatus* (dehydrogenated alcohol).
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] In the past, aldehydes were sometimes named after the corresponding alcohols, for example, *vinous aldehyde* for acetaldehyde.
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] The term *formyl group* is derived from the Latin word *formica* "ant".
[src:areca-nut/aldehyde] This word can be recognized in the simplest aldehyde, formaldehyde, and in the simplest carboxylic acid, formic acid.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The **areca nut**, also called **betel nut**, is the seed of a palm belonging to the areca genus (*Areca catechu*).
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The palm is originally native to the Philippines, but was carried widely through the tropics by the Austronesian migrations and trade since at least 1500 BCE due to its use in betel nut chewing.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It is widespread in cultivation and is considered naturalized in much of the tropical Pacific (Melanesia and Micronesia), South Asia, Southeast Asia, and parts of east Africa.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It is not to be confused with betel (*Piper betle*) leaves that are often used to wrap it.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The practice of betel nut chewing, often together with other herbs as a stimulant drug, dates back thousands of years, and continues to the present day in many countries.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Areca nut chewing is addictive due to the presence of a stimulant alkaloid, arecoline, and causes adverse health effects, mainly oral and esophageal cancers, as well as cardiovascular disease.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] When chewed with additional tobacco in its preparation (like in gutka), there is an even higher risk, especially for oral and oropharyngeal cancers.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] With tobacco it also raises the risk of fatal coronary artery disease, fatal stroke, and adverse reproductive effects, including stillbirth, premature birth, and low birth weight.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Its consumption by around 600 million people worldwide, mainly of South and Southeast Asian origin, has been described as one of the greatest public health emergencies.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The terms dates back to the 16th century, when Dutch and Portuguese sailors took the nut from India to Europe.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The areca nut is not a true nut, but rather the seed of a fruit categorized as a berry.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It is commercially available in dried, cured, and fresh forms.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] When the husk of the fresh fruit is green, the nut inside is soft enough to be cut with a typical knife.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In the ripe fruit, the husk becomes yellow or orange, and as it dries, the fruit inside hardens to a wood-like consistency.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] At that stage, the areca nut can only be sliced using a special scissors-like cutter.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Usually, for chewing, a few slices of the nut are wrapped in a betel leaf along with calcium hydroxide (slaked lime) and may include clove, cardamom, catechu resin (*kattha*), or other spices for extra flavouring.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Betel leaf has a fresh, peppery taste, but it can also be bitter to varying degrees, depending on the variety.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Areca nuts are chewed for their effects as a mild stimulant, causing a warming sensation in the body and slightly heightened alertness, although the effects vary from person to person.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In parts of India, Sri Lanka, southern China, and Southeast Asia, areca nuts are not only chewed along with betel leaf, but are also used in the preparation of Ayurvedic and traditional Chinese medicines.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Powdered areca nut is used as a constituent in some dentifrices.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Other traditional uses include the removal of tapeworms and other intestinal parasites by swallowing a few teaspoons of powdered areca nut, drunk as a decoction, or by taking tablets containing the extracted alkaloids.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] According to traditional Ayurvedic medicine, chewing areca nut and betel leaf is a good remedy against bad breath.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Diplomat Edmund Roberts noted that Chinese people would mix areca nut with *Uncaria gambir* during his visit to China in the 1830s.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] After chewing a betel nut, the red residue is generally spat out.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Accordingly, places have banned chewing this nut to avoid eyesores.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The major alkaloid in betel nut is arecoline, a non-selective partial agonist of muscarinic and nicotinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] There are other compounds, such as arecaidine, guvacine, isoguvacine, and guvacoline.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Tannins present in betel nut are mainly proanthocyanidins along with catechins and arecatannin.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Two new alkaloids were recently discovered and named acatechu A and acatechu B.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Several non-alkaloid compounds including benzenoids, terpenes, carboxylic acids, aldehydes, alcohols, and esters were also identified.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Chewing areca nut increases the risk of multiple forms of cancer and cardiovascular disease, with or without added tobacco.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Betel nut chewing causes an increased risk of head and neck cancers and esophageal cancer.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Betel quid affects almost all parts of the human body, including the brain, heart, lungs, gastrointestinal tract and reproductive organs.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It can cause myocardial infarction, cardiac arrhythmias, liver damage, asthma, type II diabetes, hyperlipidemia, metabolic syndrome, hypothyroidism, prostate hyperplasia and infertility.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Habitual chewing of areca nuts increases the risk of cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Chewing areca nuts is a cause of oral submucous fibrosis, a condition which may progress to mouth cancer.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It has also been linked to throat cancer.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] When chewed with additional tobacco in its preparation (like in gutka), there is an even higher risk for cancer, especially for oral and oropharyngeal cancers.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The harm caused by consumption of areca nuts worldwide was classified in 2017 as a "neglected global public health emergency".
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Indian government and agriculture ministry is probing the IARC report as a misconception.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Significant opposition and contradictions in the IARC report has been reported in India.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] One such contradiction being, Arecoline, one of arecanut's principal constituents, is classified under Group II B (possibly carcinogenic to humans).
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Women who chew areca nut formulations, such as *paan*, during pregnancy significantly increase adverse outcomes for the baby.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Betel quid chewing can cause stillbirth, premature birth, and low birth weight.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Using tobacco or areca nuts during pregnancy significantly increases adverse outcomes for the baby.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The habit is associated with higher incidences of preterm birth and low birth weight and height.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Biologically, these effects may be a consequence of the arecoline that is found in areca nuts.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The habit also exposes the fetus to various other toxic components linked to cancer.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In 2023, world production of areca nuts was 2.3 million tonnes, with India providing 60% of the total and Bangladesh and Myanmar as major secondary producers (table).
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] State of Karnataka in India alone produced 79.97% of country's overall production (2019-20).
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In India (the largest consumer of areca nut) and the rest of the Indian subcontinent, the preparation of nut with or without betel leaf is commonly referred to as paan.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It is available practically everywhere and is sold in ready-to-chew pouches called *pan masala* or *supari*, which is the dried form of the areca nut, as a mixture of many flavours whose primary base is dried areca nut crushed into small pieces.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Poor people, who may eat only every other day, use it to stave off hunger pangs.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] *Pan masala* with a small quantity of tobacco is called *gutka*.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The easily discarded, small plastic *supari* or *gutka* pouches are a ubiquitous pollutant of the South Asian environment.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Some of the liquid in the mouth is usually disposed of by spitting, producing bright red spots wherever the expectorate lands.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In the Maldives, areca nut chewing is very popular, but spitting is frowned upon and regarded as an unrefined, repulsive way of chewing.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Usually, people prefer to chew thin slices of the dry nut, which is sometimes roasted.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] *Killi*, a mixture of areca nut, betel, cloves, cardamom and sugar is sold in small home-made paper pouches.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Old people who have lost their teeth keep "chewing" by pounding the mixture of areca nut and betel with a small mortar and pestle.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Thailand, the consumption of areca nut has declined gradually in the last decades.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The younger generation rarely chews the substance, especially in the cities.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Most of the present-day consumption is confined to older generations, mostly people above 50.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Even so, small trays of betel leaves and sliced tender areca nut are sold in markets and used as offerings in Buddhist shrines.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In the northern Philippines, particularly the Cordillera Administrative Region, betel nut chewing remains prominent to the point that restrictions and fines have been established in urban areas such as Baguio City in the Benguet province.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] These restrictions were made under the idea that *momma* or *moma* (betel nut) chewing and spitting are improper during public transportation drivers' work hours and are considered stains to the city roads and sidewalks.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Despite these restrictions, betel nut thrives across the Cordilleran market.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] An example of its commerciality can be observed in Ifugao, one of the provinces of the Philippine Cordilleras, where betel nuts are high-demand products sourced from the province's different cities and municipalities.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Bahasa Indonesia, the betel nut is known as *makan pinang*, while in the Papua Province of Indonesia, it is known simply as *pinang*.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The Pinang scissor was developed specifically for cutting it.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Papua New Guinea (PNG), betel nuts are referred to in Tok Pisin as *buai*, and grow abundantly on the northern coast, in Wewak and Madang.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] A controversial ban on selling and chewing betel nut in public places in Port Moresby, introduced in 2014 by the governor, was lifted in 2017.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Because the popular nut continued to be smuggled in, prices rose dramatically.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Police enforced the ban rigorously, and in 2015 two betel nut sellers died in Hanuabada after police reservists fired on a crowd.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The governor of Port Moresby introduced another ban on the nut, restricted to an area in the business district of the city in July 2023.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] However many people make a living out of selling betel nut, so are resistant to bans in their areas.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] On Manus Island, young men are exposed to piracy when they use small boats to travel to the northern coast to purchase betel nuts to trade, and several have disappeared.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Australia, the importation, use, and sale of areca nut is banned, but it has been sold illegally in several South Asian supermarkets.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Hainan and Hunan Province, China, where Xiangtan is a center of use and processing, a wide range of old and young people consume areca nut daily.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Most, though, consume the dried variety of the nut by itself, without the betel leaves.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Some people also consume the areca nut in its raw, fresh form with or without the betel leaves.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Betel nuts are sold mostly by old women merchants, but the dried version can be found in shops that sell tea, alcohol, and cigarettes.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Taiwan, bags of 20 to 40 areca nuts are purchased fresh daily by a large number of consumers.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The latter is usually elevated one meter above the street, and measures less than 3 by 2 m.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Large picture windows comprise two or more of the walls, allowing those who pass by a complete view of the interior.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Within such a shop, a sexily dressed young woman, a "betel nut beauty", can be seen preparing betel and areca nuts.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Shops are often identified by colorful (commonly green) LED lamps or neon lights that frame the windows or that are arranged radially above a store.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Customers stop on the side of the road and wait for the girls to bring their betel and areca nut to their vehicles.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The habit of chewing betel nut is often associated with blue-collar labor industries such as long-haul transportation, construction, or fishing.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Workers in these labor-intensive industries use betel nut for its stimulating effect, but it also becomes a tool for socializing with coworkers.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] For example, studies have shown chewing betel nut is prevalent among taxi, bus and truck drivers, who rely on the stimulating effect of betel nut to cope with long work hours.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] For these reasons, oral cancer has been identified as a leading cause of death in professions with high betel nut-chewing rates.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In the United States, areca nut is not a controlled or specially taxed substance and may be found in some Asian grocery stores.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] However, importation of areca nut in a form other than whole or carved kernels of nuts can be stopped at the discretion of US Customs officers on the grounds of food, agricultural, or medicinal drug violations.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In the United Kingdom the betel nut is legal.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Possession of areca nut or betel leaf is banned in the UAE and is a punishable offence.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Chewing the mixture of areca nut and betel leaf constitutes an important and popular cultural activity in many South Asian, Southeast Asian, East Asian and Oceanic countries.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Why or when the areca nut and the betel leaf were first combined into one psychoactive drug is not known.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Archaeological evidence from Thailand, Indonesia, and the Philippines suggests they have been used in tandem for at least 4,000 years.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The oldest unequivocal evidence of betel chewing is from the Philippines, specifically that of several individuals found in a burial pit in the Duyong Cave site of Palawan island dated to around 2680±250 BCE.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The dentition of the skeletons is stained, typical of betel chewers.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The grave also includes *Anadara* shells used as containers of lime, one of which still contained lime.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Burial sites in Bohol dated to the first millennium CE also show the distinctive reddish stains characteristic of betel chewing.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] From the Philippines, it spread back to Taiwan, as well as onwards to the rest of Austronesia and in neighboring cultures through trade and migration.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Vietnam, the areca nut and the betel leaf are such important symbols of love and marriage that in Vietnamese the phrase "matters of betel and areca" (*chuyện trầu cau*) is synonymous with marriage.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The tradition of chewing areca nuts starts the talk between the groom's parents and the bride's parents about the young couple's marriage.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Therefore, the leaves and juices are used ceremonially in Vietnamese weddings.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The folk tale explaining the origin of this Vietnamese tradition is a good illustration of the belief that the combination of areca nut and the betel leaf is ideal to the point they are practically inseparable, like an idealized married couple.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Formerly, in both India and Sri Lanka, it was a custom of the royalty to chew areca nut with betel leaf.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Kings had special attendants whose duty it was to carry a box with all the necessary ingredients for a good chewing session.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] There was also a custom for lovers to chew areca nut and betel leaf together, because of its breath-freshening and relaxant properties.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] A sexual symbolism thus became attached to the chewing of the nut and the leaf.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The areca nut represented the male principle, and the betel leaf the female principle.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Considered an auspicious ingredient in Hinduism and some schools of Buddhism, the areca nut is still used along with betel leaf in religious ceremonies, and also while honoring individuals in much of southern Asia.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Assam, as well as most of its neighbouring Northeastern India states, areca nuts are preferably consumed in fermented form, which is supposed to make the fruit harder and sweeter.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The raw nut may also be eaten during certain seasons when the fermented variety becomes unavailable, although it has more ritual importance.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Standard-sized pieces of the nut and leaf are usually consumed in combination with lime and a bit of tobacco.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Assam, betel nut and leaf has indispensable cultural value; offering betel leaf and nut, (together known as *gua*) constitutes a part of social greeting and socialising.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] It is a tradition to offer *pan-tamul* (betel leaves and raw areca nut) to guests immediately upon arrival, and after tea or meals, served in a brass plate with stands called *bota*.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In traditional Assamese societies carrying a pouch of *tamul-pan* upon one's person during journeys or during farming activities, and sharing of the same, was an essential requirement.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Among the Assamese, the areca nut also has a variety of uses during religious and marriage ceremonies, where it has the role of a fertility symbol.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] No religious ritual is complete without the offering of *tamul-pan* to the gods and spirits as well as to the assembled guests.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] A tradition from Upper Assam is to invite guests to wedding receptions by offering a few areca nuts with betel leaves.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] During Bihu, the *husori* players are offered areca nuts and betel leaves by each household while their blessings are solicited.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Spanish mariner Álvaro de Mendaña reported observing Solomon Islanders chewing the nut and the leaf with caustic lime, and the manner in which the habit stained their mouths red.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] He noted the friendly and genial chief Malope, on Santa Isabel Island, would offer him the combination as a token of friendship every time they met.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In Bhutan, the areca nut is called *doma*.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The soft and moist raw areca nut is very potent.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] When chewed it can cause palpitation and vasoconstriction.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] This form is eaten in the lower regions of Bhutan and in North Bengal, where the nut is cut into half and put into a local *paan* leaf with a generous amount of lime.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] In the rest of Bhutan the raw nut, with the husk on, is fermented such that the husk rots and is easy to extract.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The fermented doma has a putrid odour, which can be smelled at a distance.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Traditionally, the fragrant nut is cut in half and placed on top of a cone made of local betel leaf, which has a dash of lime put inside.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] "Myth has it that the inhabitants of Bhutan traditionally known as Monyul, the land of Monpas where Buddhism did not reach lived on raw flesh, drank blood, and chewed bones.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] After the arrival of Guru Rinpoche in the eighth century, he stopped the people from eating flesh and drinking blood and created a substitute which is betel leaf, lime and areca nut.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Today, chewing doma has become a custom.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Doma is served after meals, during rituals and ceremonies.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The addition of tobacco leaf to the chewing mixture is a relatively recent innovation, as tobacco was not introduced from the Americas until the colonial era.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Reasons for starting to consume areca nuts appears to involve complex psychosocial factors.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] The husk, which is between 50 and 75 percent of the weight and volume of an areca fruit, serves as a source of fiber for the construction industry.
[src:areca-nut/areca-nut] Typically, these fibers are considered to be waste, but can be used to strengthen construction materials.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:areca-nut/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:areca-nut/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
